No one thought that the Earth was flat back then. Ok, few crazy people did, 
but that is still true today. Among the educated classes of Columbus' day, 
the belief in a flat earth was no more popular then than it is now.

Christopher Columbus actually believed that Earth was more of a pear shape, 
with a huge bulge elevating the garden of Eden far above the rest. He 
believed that Asia was far larger than it was, and that the Earth as a 
whole far smaller. He believed that he could reach Asia by sailing over a 
relatively small distance of ocean.

Most European intellectuals trusted the reasoning of those Ancient Greeks 
who calculated that Earth was a sphere very close to its actual size. Their 
estimated distance from Western Europe to Eastern Asia was fairly accurate 
too. Most thought that he would have to travel this whole distance across 
the open ocean, which was far longer than contemporary ships would be able 
to cross without making many stops for repairs and provisions. Some thought 
it might work if he was able to stop on enough islands along the way, but 
few were willing to bet their lives or fortunes on the existence of such 
islands at just the right locations. Some correctly guessed that there 
might be a large landmass which would block the passage to Asia, even 
though these experts typically falsely assumed that the lands would be 
uninhabited. That was because they thought all living humans and other land 
animals were descended from those which Noah's Ark rescued from the Great 
Flood, and they did not see how their descendants could have migrated that 
far across the open ocean in just a few thousand years.

(Book #2, Hadith #9)-Sahih Bukhari:
‘Narrated 'Abdullah bin 'Amr: The Prophet said, "A MUSLIM is the one who

Muslims.  Or in other words, whenever the word, Muslim, is mentioned, it

hands(, i.e. violence or killing).
